 of his day. It is also the record of a friendship. As Peter Josyph remarks in his introduction, "With a good correspondence, as with the blowing between horn players improvising off each other's riffs, it isn't easy to say whether it's art or society because it is both of them at once. This is a book about two men who value a friendship balanced upon words; men for whose friendship the phone is a thief; men who are comfortable with the U.S. mail."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAuthors, Americany20th centuryvCorrespondence. 4aGeneral Interest : Autobiography, Biography and Memoir. 4aLanguage Arts : Composition and Rhetoric Studies. 4aLiterature : American Literature. 4aLiterature : Literature. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Letters.2bisacsh1 aJosyph, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJosyph, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143842720140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438427201423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438427201/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles